\f0\b\fs28 \cf0 HOMER Coding Challenge: Build a Weather App Prototype\
\pard\pardeftab720\ri0\sl276\slmult1\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs18 \cf0 Prototype a simple weather app to demonstrate full stack web application development expertise. We\'92d like you to create a simple single-page application and a corresponding simple RESTful, GraphQL or gRPC API.\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\ri0\sl276\slmult1\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs24 \cf0 Prototype Specifications
\f1\b0\fs18  \
For the frontend of the app, the user should, in some way, enter a US zip code. Once the zip code is entered, the 5 day forecast should be displayed as a list, and clicking any of the day elements should show more weather information for that day. Here is one way the display could look:\
\
\
\
While we provide you with a zip of weather icons, there is no specific design spec for the prototype, so you have the freedom to implement your own look and feel. It should however be responsive, work well on various, reasonably sized screens and be generally pleasant to use. One requirement: because we are very conscious about skin safety here at HOMER, we ask that you additionally display the UV index for at least the current day in the interface. :)\
\
For the API, you will need to create a single RESTful, GraphQL, or gRPC endpoint that aggregates two endpoints provided at the free tier from {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://openweathermap.org/api"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 \ul \ulc2 https://openweathermap.org/api}}. The two endpoints are the the 5 day, 3 hours forecast {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://openweathermap.org/forecast5"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 \ul \ulc2 https://openweathermap.org/forecast5}} and the UV index {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://openweathermap.org/api/uvi"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 \ul \ulc2 https://openweathermap.org/api/uvi}} . You can sign up for for the open weather API at {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://openweathermap.org/appid"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 \ul \ulc2 https://openweathermap.org/appid}}.\
\

